== Working locally

****
If you are able to write and run Python 3 scripts locally, then you should
do so.

You are not required to use _TermCast_.
****

.Run Python scripts locally like this
----
$ python3 hello.py
----

****
When ready, upload your work to _Einstein_: link:/einstein/[here].
****

// //////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////
== Using _TermCast_

****
If you are not able to run Python scripts locally, then you should use
_TermCast_ to develop and run your Python scripts on the school's Linux
server:

- _TermCast_ is here: link:/termcast/[link]
- https://drive.google.com/file/d/1QNfU1ESzIaV2Ycd7QszQIRRtfrFiQyGz/view?usp=sharing[_TermCast_,
  python3 and uploading to _Einstein_]
  (short video, about five minutes)

*You must use Chrome!*

Other browsers might not work (it is known that IE and Safari do not work).
****

// //////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////
=== Sessions

****
When using _TermCast_, you can create two _sessions_.

To create a second session, either:

- click "split" at the top-left-hand side of the screen, or
- use "Control-\#" (hold down the "Control" key and hit "#" +
  (this shortcut also jumps back and forwards between sessions).
****

****
A typical workflow involves using one session for running
Python scripts, and a second session for editing those scripts.
****

// //////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////
=== Editor (nano)

****
To write Python scripts, you will need a text editor.

On _TermCast_, use the "nano" text editor.

You can launch the nano text editor like this:

----
$ nano hello.py
----
****

****
In nano:

- use "Control-o" to save (or "write Out") your file, and
- use "Control-x" to exit the editor.
****

// //////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////
=== Running Python scripts

****
Run Python scripts at the terminal prompt like this:

----
$ python3 hello.py
----
****

// //////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////
=== Uploading Python scripts

****
On _TermCast_, there is a command named "einstein" for uploading your work to
_Einstein_.
****

****
Use this command like this:

----
$ einstein hello.py
----

The command will report whether your script is correct or incorrect.

You can view the resulting report on the course web site:

- link:/einstein/report.html[]

You will have to reload this page every time you upload a new script.
****

